@cangencer Using JMH submitting 100 no-op tasks to ForkJoinPool.commonPool and waiting for their completion by checking future.isDone takes on average 300μs. So it's not that much pain.
@mtopolnik It's not a lambda, but a method we call. We can check if the declaringClass of close method is the Processor class:
if (p.getClass().getMethod("close").getDeclaringClass() == Processor.class)
    // ignore the close method
I benchmarked this too. This check took 1.3μs, while directly executing a no-op runnable took 1.7μs. I think it's not worth the complexity, we're not on a hot path.
